        "id": 282357,
        "name": "BG",
        "username": "givens",
        "avatar_template": "/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/g/85f322/{size}.png",
        "created_at": "2026-01-07T19:02:58.147Z",
        "cooked": "<p>I am someone who generally enjoys privacy, but I am not in a situation where my liberty or safety is at stake.</p>\n<p>I find Apple privacy sometimes opaque and misleading.  They market their devices using privacy as a differentiator but their privacy policy describes how they share much data with partners that I find to be personal. I have not determined how to prevent sharing or lock down my privacy for Apple apps and perhaps others</p>\n<p>I remain concerned about E2EE on the iOS Signal app. My specific concern is that the input generally uses the Apple keyboard, and the keyboard is predictive. This suggests it is aware of what I am typing prior to it being E2EE on the Signal app.  Potentially every keystroke is exposed</p>\n<p>I have a sense these operations happen on device, but I do not know what Apple stores or sends to servers.  Is anyone aware of privacy limitations of this?</p>\n<p>I would love to understand Apple privacy better  it may be deliberately opaque.</p>\n<p>I did a cursory search on this forum  for related topics and did not find anything that explained Apple keyboard privacy limitations in regard to the Signal app. I hope I did not overlook the answer.</p>",
