      {
        "id": 282374,
        "name": "",
        "username": "desert_nip",
        "avatar_template": "/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/d/ccd318/{size}.png",
        "created_at": "2026-01-07T23:15:24.290Z",
        "cooked": "<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"zetabeta\" data-post=\"2\" data-topic=\"74085\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n<img alt=\"\" width=\"24\" height=\"24\" src=\"https://community.signalusers.org/user_avatar/community.signalusers.org/zetabeta/48/54310_2.png\" class=\"avatar\"> zetabeta:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<p>signal org cannot secure underlying operating system. ultimately no one can guarantee what is going on in apple devices.</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>I absolutely agree with that. E2EE means exactly what it says: Encryption is ensured from sender to receiver. What happens on the end devices is something Signal cannot control, whether that be a spying OS or a keylogger (from whatever source). If you want to have true privacy and security for your chats, you have to be able to trust your end device.</p>",
